            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Raised in the foggy, evergreen suburbs of Portland, Oregon, Morgan Riley was the pragmatic daughter of a civil engineer and a high school English teacher. Her childhood was a blend of structured logic and creative inquiry, setting the stage for her future. She left the Pacific Northwest for the Bay Area to attend UC Berkeley, initially drawn to the abstract puzzles of neuroscience. However, a sophomore year course in Human-Computer Interaction sparked a revelation. She switched her major to Cognitive Science, fascinated by the intersection of the human mind and digital interfaces.\n\nHer career began with a coveted internship at a mid-size SaaS company in SoMa. Morgan quickly proved her value, possessing a unique ability to translate user psychology into tangible software features. She rose through the ranks, from Associate to her current role as a Senior Product Manager at a leading enterprise analytics firm. Her work is her craft: she spends her days mediating between engineering teams, designers, and customer feedback, shaping the tools that thousands of professionals use daily.\n\nMorgan\u2019s life is anchored in her NoPa apartment, a sunny one-bedroom in a classic Victorian. Her daily routine begins with a 3.5-mile bicycle commute, weaving through the bike lanes of The Wiggle to her downtown office. This ride is her meditation, a way to process the day ahead and decompress on the way home. Evenings are often spent with her tight-knit group of friends\u2014a mix of former colleagues and Berkeley alumni\u2014grabbing dinner on Divisadero or catching an indie film at the Roxie. A long-term relationship ended a year ago, a painful but clarifying turning point that refocused her energy on her own ambitions.\n\nSan Francisco is more than a workplace for Morgan; it\u2019s a landscape of opportunity and recreation. Weekends are for trail runs in the Presidio or exploring farmers' markets. Her greatest aspiration, brewing in the back of her mind, is to step out on her own. She dreams of launching a startup: a productivity app designed to reduce cognitive load for busy professionals, a direct application of her education and lived experience. She sees her future not just in managing products, but in building one from the ground up."
